  "prompt": "Is money laundering unlawful?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is unlawful in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the money appear as if it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under several statutes, including the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986. Violations can lead to severe penalties, including hefty fines and imprisonment.\n\nSimilarly, in the European Union, the Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) set out rigorous requirements for financial institutions and other entities to prevent money laundering activities. Member states are required to implement these directives into their national laws.\n\nInternational cooperation in combating money laundering is also significant, with organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) setting global standards and promoting effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with substantial legal and financial consequences.",
